	<texts id="2001">
		<paragraph indent="0" tabs="" style="normal" height="0" width="400" y="+6" x="12" type="text"><![CDATA[<TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT FACE="Verdana" SIZE="13" COLOR="#000000" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0">In compositions where we want to discuss the arguments for and against something, it is sometimes necessary to discuss hypothetical situations. To do this, we use a verb form known as the conditional. This is often found in sentences with an 'if' clause, for example:</FONT></P></TEXTFORMAT>]]></paragraph>
		<paragraph indent="0" tabs="" style="normal" height="0" width="400" y="+0" x="12" type="text"><![CDATA[<TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT FACE="Verdana" SIZE="13" COLOR="#000000" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0">If we removed language differences, we would find it easier to understand each other's point of view.</FONT></P></TEXTFORMAT>]]></paragraph>
		<paragraph indent="0" tabs="" style="normal" height="0" width="400" y="+0" x="12" type="text"><![CDATA[<TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT FACE="Verdana" SIZE="13" COLOR="#000000" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0">However, we can also use the conditional without an 'if' clause. For example:</FONT></P></TEXTFORMAT>]]></paragraph>
		<paragraph indent="0" tabs="" style="normal" height="0" width="400" y="+0" x="12" type="text"><![CDATA[<TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT FACE="Verdana" SIZE="13" COLOR="#000000" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0">It is generally agreed that a common language would make international travel much easier for everyone.</FONT></P></TEXTFORMAT>]]></paragraph>
